The first was Olaf Worm, who published an edition in the following year at Copenhagen‚ vindicating the speech against Wolf ’s onslaught, while acknowledging the presence in it of certain flaws of style and diction. Weiske followed with a yet more elaborate defence 1; which begins with an ironical proof (by Wolf’s methods) that Wolf ’s edition itself is really the work of a pseudo-Wolf. The quarrel of the critice is still sub iudice. Great names have appeared on either side: for Wolf, among others stand, Niebuhr, Orelli (who prints the pro Marcello at the end of the rhetorical works), and Kayser3 on the conservative side, Drumann, Teuffel, Hahn, Klotz, Richter, C.
